ath, Irska"},"cs":{"1200–":"1200–Zesnulý","1200–Male":"1200–Zesnulý","1210–Male":"1210–Zesnulý","1202–Female":"1202–Zesnulá","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1871–Male":"1871–Zesnulý","1155–Male":"1155–Zesnulý","1182–Female":"1182–Zesnulá","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1871":"1871","1299":"1299","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1182":"1182","Caernaevon Castle, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, Anglie","Slane Castle, County Meath, Ireland":"Slane Castle, County Meath, Irsko"},"da":{"1200–":"1200–Afdød","1200–Male":"1200–Afdød","1210–Male":"1210–Afdød","1202–Female":"1202–Afdød","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1871–Male":"1871–Afdød","1155–Male":"1155–Afdød","1182–Female":"1182–Afdød","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1871":"1871","1299":"1299","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1182":"1182","Caernaevon Castle, Cumberland, England":"Cumbraland, England","Slane Castle, County Meath, Ireland":"Slane Castle, County Meath, Irland"},"nl":{"1200–":"1200–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1202–Female":"1202–Overleden","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1871–Male":"1871–Overleden","1155–Male":"1155–Overleden","1182–Female":"1182–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1871":"1871","1299":"1299","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1182":"1182","Caernaevon Castle, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","Slane Castle, County Meath, Ireland":"Slane Castle, County Meath, Ierland"},"en":{"1200–":"1200–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1202–Female":"1202–Deceased","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1871–Male":"1871–Deceased","1155–Male":"1155–Deceased","1182–Female":"1182–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1871":"1871","1299":"1299","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1182":"1182","Caernaevon Castle, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","Slane Castle, County Meath, Ireland":"Slane Castle, County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fleming","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, from Middle English <i>fleming</i>. The word reflects a Norman French form of Old French <i>flamanc</i> ‘Fleming’, from the stem <i>flam-</i> + the ancient Germanic suffix <i>-ing</i>. In the Middle Ages there was considerable commercial intercourse between England and the Netherlands, particularly in the wool trade, and many Flemish weavers and dyers settled in England. This surname is also common in south and east Scotland and in Ireland, where it is sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Fleming \"Flandrensis\" was born in 1200, in Cumberland, England, his father, Sir Archembald \"Gillespic\" le Fleming \"Flandrensis\", was 45 and his mother, Lady Archembald le Fleming, was 19. He had at least 1 son with Lady Richard le Fleming."},"et":{"1200–":"1200–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1202–Female":"1202–Surnud","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1871–Male":"1871–Surnud","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1182–Female":"1182–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1871":"1871","1299":"1299","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1182":"1182","Caernaevon Castle, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","Slane Castle, County Meath, Ireland":"Slane Castle, County Meath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1200–":"1200–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1202–Female":"1202–Kuollut","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1871–Male":"1871–Kuollut","1155–Male":"1155–Kuollut","1182–Female":"1182–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1871":"1871","1299":"1299","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1182":"1182","Caernaevon Castle, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","Slane Castle, County Meath, Ireland":"Slane Castle, County Meath, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1200–":"1200–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1210–Male":"1210–Décédé","1202–Female":"1202–Décédée","1234–1299":"1234–1299","1871–Male":"1871–Décédé","1155–Male":"1155–Décédé","1182–F